How do I approach designing software?

I approach software design in a structured and intentional way. I begin by reviewing requirements, identifying core components, and planning how those components interact before writing code. 
In this 3D scene project, that meant deciding object placement, scale, camera positioning, and lighting strategy before implementation. I followed an iterative milestone process—building the scene 
step by step, refining spatial relationships, and improving realism through textures and lighting. This layered approach helps reduce errors and makes future adjustments easier. The same structured 
design mindset can be applied to future software systems, data applications, and visualization tools.

How do I approach developing programs?

I develop programs incrementally and test functionality at each stage. In this project, I verified object rendering before adding textures and confirmed lighting calculations before refining placement. 
Iteration played a major role; I frequently adjusted coordinates, scaling, and shader parameters to improve realism and performance. Throughout the milestones, my development approach evolved from focusing 
on simply rendering objects to thinking more about modularity, performance, and maintainability. By the end of the project, I was developing with greater intention and structure.

How can computer science and computational graphics help me reach my goals?

Computer science strengthens my analytical thinking and technical problem-solving skills, both of which are essential for building efficient systems. Computational graphics and visualization expanded my 
understanding of transformations, lighting models, and GPU interaction, while reinforcing strong C++ development practices. These skills enhance my educational growth by deepening my programming foundation 
and support my professional goals by improving my ability to design structured, scalable, and visually meaningful technical solutions.
